ets live and learn in an environment of trust  Their daily lives and conduct are regulated by the traditions and rules of the Institute and a very simple code of honor  Cadets trust one another because their word is their bond  Conduct Above all else  cadets are expected to conduct themselves as men and women of character at all times  Exemplary conduct both at and away from the Institute reflects credit on the cadet  the Corps  and the Institute  Civility Cadets are expected commit to respectful living  treating everyone with dignity and fairness  Cadets come to understand the impact of their behavior on others and strive to exemplify civility  More about the Honor Code Share this entry Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Google  Share on Linkedin Share on Tumblr Share on Reddit Share by Mail Stories   Videos Stories   Video Home Stories Slideshows Day in the Life Video Library Admissions Video More About Life at VMI Cadets Academics Athletics Challenge Alumni Faculty and Staff Apply Now Viewbook Links College Fairs FAQs Financial Aid Tuition   Fees Schedule VMI s Institutional Profile Follow  Then lead  Resources VMI CEEB Code  005858 Financial Aid FAFSA Code  003753 Students and their families are encouraged to use a variety of information sources to select a college and major  The State Council of Higher Education for Virginia  SCHEV  provides one such source that is available here  Contact Us VMI Office of Admissions 319 Letcher Avenue Lexington  VA 24450 P  540 464 7211 P  800 767 4207 F  540 464 7746 admissions vmi edu Don t do ordinary  EXPERIENCE VISIT APPLY COSTS   AID CONTACT Stories   Video You are here  Home   Experience   Stories   Video   Life at VMI   New Cadet Oath Ceremony Stories   Video You are here  Home   Experience   Stories   Video   Life at VMI   New Cadet Oath Ceremony Stories   Video Stories   Video You are here  Home   Experience   Stories   Video   Life at VMI   New Cadet Oath Ceremony You are here  Home   Experience   Stories   Video   Life at VMI   New Cadet Oath Ceremony You are here You are here Home Home  Experience Experience  Stories   Video Stories   Video  Life at VMI Life at VMI  New Cadet Oath Ceremony New Cadet Oath Ceremony New Cadet Oath Ceremony January 9  2014 in Life at VMI  Slideshows  by Kate Since its founding in 1839  VMI cadets have been bound by a code of honorable behavior  The cadet run Honor Court was established as a continuously operating body beginning in 1908  The heart of the VMI honor system is the Honor Code  A cadet does not lie  cheat  steal  nor tolerate those who do  Single Sanction The sanction for any breech of honor is dismissal  When rats sign the Matriculation Book  they commit themselves to a life of honesty and integrity  If their commitment is not complete  their stay at the Institute may be short  Trust Cadets live and learn in an environment of trust  Their daily lives and conduct are regulated by the traditions and rules of the Institute and a very simple code of honor  Cadets trust one another because their word is their bond  Conduct Above all else  cadets are expected to conduct themselves as men and women of character at all times  Exemplary conduct both at and away from the Institute reflects credit on the cadet  the Corps  and the Institute  Civility Cadets are expected commit to respectful living  treating everyone with dignity and fairness  Cadets come to understand the impact of their behavior on others and strive to exemplify civility  More about the Honor Code Share this entry Share on Facebook Share on Twitter Share on Google  Share on Linkedin Share on Tumblr Share on Reddit Share by Mail Stories   Videos Stories   Video Home Stories Slideshows Day in the Life Video Library Admissions Video More About Life at VMI Cadets Academics Athletics Challenge Alumni Faculty and Staff Apply Now New Cadet Oath Ceremony January 9  2014 in Life at VMI  Slideshows  by Kate Since its founding in 1839  VMI cadets have been bound by a code of honor